There is, in this great world, a generalized and inevitable law that implies that two things cannot be found in the same place at the same time.
There is no way to break that rule and do not try too hard, because it will end up hurting itself.
Although particle physics is a very complex world, it has been shown that there is also a law of these characteristics in it: Pauli's principle of exclusion, which stipulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state"; a "state" which consists, grossly, of some of its characteristics.
Physicists classify particles into two categories.
On the one hand, we find good citizens called fermions, who wisely obey Pauli’s principle.
