Bitcoin differs from other systems with types of virtual currencies such as “credits”, used to advance in a video game and that can be won by playing or bought (and even sometimes exchanged).
The social network Facebook also developed this type of system.
But in every exchange a central authority controls and deals with changes.
With bitcoin, all network nodes are at the same time accounting book stores, verifiers, currency issuers and buyers and sellers.
How does that network work?
Each transaction between two users is actually made between two email addresses in the form of email.
A user can choose a different address for each payment, thus guaranteeing anonymity.
A set of information connected to this transaction is electronically signed through a double-key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that bitcoin changes are contained in the public account book, which is spread throughout the network.
The key milestone is to write that new transaction in that book.
This goes through the resolution of a mathematical challenge launched to computers and the winner, a sort of provisional central banker, will have the privilege of adding that complementary line.
This is a phase of file scraping, i.e., of transforming a large file into a shorter and unique numerical footprint.
Computers "take" the new transaction and add a number before "trotting" the set.
The goal is to find the number that offers a particular footprint (more zero at the beginning).
Once that number is found, the other nodes easily verify that it is the good one.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the chain of sets of the other transactions; any modification would change the footprint.
If, to commit a fraud, a user would like to pay twice with the same money very quickly (in less than ten minutes), the network would only accept as valid one of the two transactions; the other would remain orphaned, as both have different footprints.
The computer that solves the challenge takes 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, that reward is divided into two regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible to the 100 millionth, leaving a broad margin.
The difficulty of this challenge is also revealed in each increase in computing power.
The life of the network already has its heights.
Websites offering services for Bitcoin have been attacked and bitcoins have been stolen in deposit.
“The default used does not affect the same protocol,” says Pierre Noizat, who has just launched Paymium, a real-currency payment company that uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also takes into account the possibility of money laundering thanks to this anonymous service.
But cash has the same flaw.
Weight actors like Wikipedia reject payments of this type.
Others, such as the WordPress platform, accept them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron, of the Weizmann Institute in Israel, analyzed the accounting book and showed that about 80% of bitcoins do not circulate.
In November, the “giant discounts” were launched.
“<0x24>30,000 was exchanged,” says Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, who converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, author of a pedagogical book on that currency, believes in the potential of this technology as well as in the transaction network.
Its system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (in real currency) or a contactless mobile payment, but it uses Bitcoin to validate transactions, which thus come out cheaper.
The carrier, in addition, manages his identity and can therefore remain anonymous.
The system is easy to set up in stores, which do not have to install new terminals or software.
It is enough to provide them with an address that a phone can “photograph and recognize,” says Pierre Noizat, who claims to have thousands of users.
There is a general movement to review hierarchical systems by more horizontal systems.
“It will take a while for Bitcoin to be imposed, but in 2013 there could be a change,” he predicted.
Moreover, in its report, the ECB plans to reassess the various risks, now considered high, in case this currency succeeds.
