A Constitution with Foreclosures in Egypt
It is a new double or nothing from President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt is more divided than ever in terms of the constitutional declaration, which gives it provisionally full powers, he decided to play the whole for the whole.
He surprised everyone on Wednesday, when he announced that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the next day.
Just a week ago, the Head of State had given that Assembly two more months to finish his work.
And almost two years ago, Egypt used a provisional text, which has been amended several times, which weakens institutional stability and leads to judicial bribes.
This new initiative has only increased the fracture in the country.
For his opponents, the president persists in his "autocratic delirium" and continues to "tray his word" and "piss the law".
On the part of its supporters, it is ensured that this is a measure to speed up the institutional and political crisis and accelerate the transition process.
A referendum should be held within the next 15 days.
A very short period of time that forces the Brothers to give up their project of explaining the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the president, it is also a way to regain popular and democratic legitimacy while the controversy is causing devastation across the country.
Mohamed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote in favor of him, as he said in an interview with the American weekly Time.
Given that that appeal has been voted very quickly, it contains an ultimatum for the Egyptian people: "Either vote my text or I keep the powers full", powers that are supposed to come to an end with the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in that strange environment in which 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, Islamist in its vast majority, voted on the text yesterday.
Most liberals did not attend the call.
In mid-November, just before the constitutional declaration, they had closed the door because they thought they could not make their views valid.
The representatives of human rights, religious minorities and civil society did the same.
In order to achieve the necessary quorum, 11 people, alternate members, were added in a hurry yesterday morning.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
As expected, the voted articles have been unanimously.
The commentators, on the other hand, are gratified by the fact that one of the few discrepancies of the day has been expressed practically at the time of prayer, so many members of the committee came to think that the Watch of the Constituent was wrong.
The text, which was still being voted on yesterday afternoon, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2 remains the same as in the 1971 Constitution, which stipulated that "the principles of Sharia constitute the principal source of law".
The Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a fundamental claim, hoped that "the principles" could be replaced by "the rules", which would have allowed for stricter application.
For Islamists, that this article has not been modified is a guarantee of their good will and respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
The liberals call it hypocritical and consider it to be nothing more than an advertising scam.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They refer, in particular, to article 220, which confers on Al-Azhar University an advisory role, in particular for anyone who has to confirm their compliance with Sharia law.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, it is disturbing because “people called to speak are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
Here we see the premises of a theocracy."
The fears of the liberals are also heightened by the fact that the next rector of the university would be much less moderate than the current.
“For now, there is no specific religious involvement.
With this Constitution we are in the framework of the civil state.
Most of the lawyers who have worked on that text are not ulemas but university students, some of them trained in the French system,” explains Alexis Blouet, who prepares a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he acknowledges that there may be some ambiguity around article 220, as the terms employed imitate the religious vocabulary.
"We are specifically referring to the term iqh [Islamic jurisprudence, ndlr].
And the question that could be raised in the future would be to what extent are the civil judges competent to judge above all of this.”
Beyond its religious character, the text voted yesterday has received many criticisms regarding the extended powers conferred on the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood will claim that they are few compared to those they were during the previous regime.
Another conflicting point: the powers conferred on the army.
According to the wishes of the military, the revision of the defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a national defence council.
Neither will the prosecution of civilians in military courts be banned, as human rights associations have requested.
These also showed their concerns about the text, which they consider libertarian.
The crime of blasphemy continues and, from now on, insults are prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially that of the press.
In addition, no article emphasizes the protection of women, emphasizes Heba Morayef, of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive thing has been the prohibition of torture in accordance with article 36.
The word was not included in the previous constitution.
Although the Egyptian president was due to go out on television last night, demonstrations are scheduled for this noon.
Supporters of the head of state protested on Saturday.
