Is it an office similar to our NK<0xC3><0x9A> or is it organized otherwise?
As for the offices, such as the NK<0xC3><0x9A>, there is the Bundesrechnungshof, with an organization similar to ours, with a college as well, the only thing is that in your case it is structured in a slightly different way, but in principle both offices evolve in parallel.
The jurisdictions are also somewhat analogous, however, while Germany has a federal organization, the Courts of Auditors are even at this level. In this regard it differs slightly from our system.
The Federal Court of Auditors (BRH) can only control federal money, which we here call state funds.
The public funds, which are managed by the regions and municipalities, there, in Germany, are monitored by the Federal Court of Auditors.
In terms of local legislation, is it simpler than ours?
In general, I would not like to establish a comparison without concrete data. However, Germany remains a model in some respects, but it cannot be precise what is best.
Could it be better, for example, with regard to the quality of the inspectors?
Of course not, but, I repeat, I don’t like to make such comparisons.
It is necessary to say that even those countries that we take as a model must face a large number of problems.
If it weren't, you wouldn't have any benefit to collaborate with our office, would you?
As far as the legislation of our country is concerned, what did the amendment of the Public Procurement Act mean for its Office?
Given that the period of validity of this amendment is relatively short, it has not yet been expressed in the control actions.
Since we carry out ex post checks, there is a certain delay.
For now, it is observed in the process of preparing for future controls: we have launched a new tool for "not-economic risk detection", through which we have passed almost 14,000 public procurements, which have been analyzed. The changes will be perfectly reflected here, as the limits are modified, the conditions of the similar process are rectified.
Do you think that the adoption of this law is beneficial or, rather, a bulwark for the bureaucratic system?
I think this law is certainly a step in the right direction and I hope that is the case.
The problem that can arise is that the legislation "resists" and that it is impossible to comply with it.
Already under the above regulations, controlled persons were bound by the contractor (for example, in the case of regional operational programmes of the regional council), and every law that was not respected in the field of public procurement meant a violation of the budgetary discipline.
Does it make sense, then, to harden the law in this way?
I don't think so.
The system must exclude those who want to attack or take advantage of it and not punish those who commit a formal decision, which has no impact on decision-making.
Such a system will only create greater bureaucratic pressure.
And how do you get out of this?
We’ll see where this initiated path leads us.
The Prime Minister has recently stated that the SDG would not bother employers with controls of the so-called <0xC5><0xA0>varc system, with reference to the fact that it is autonomous only on paper.
Is the <0xC5><0xA0>varc system banned or allowed?
The law must be regulated in some way and, if it prohibits anything, then not even the Prime Minister of the Government can prevent the functioning of the Office that is obliged to carry out such checks and demand obligations.
He may say, "We have changed the law and allowed it," but he cannot say that we will do as if nothing.
In the Public Procurement Act, the legislation is quite strict as to the way in which it should act formally, and that is how it should be in order to protect public competition.
But, on the other hand, it is tragic that the candidate with the best offer is excluded for failing to meet the formal requirements.
The law will never be perfect, but its application must be correct, which is, in my opinion, what we lack.
