Poland and the cosmos.
At the ministerial meeting of the countries of the European Space Agency held last week, Poland was accepted as the twelfth member of the ESA. It is the second ESA member of the former bloc of Eastern Europe, after the Czech Republic, which became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland began an intensive collaboration with ESA in 1994 and participated in the Agency's project commission in the following years.
However, the path from Poland to the cosmos began much earlier.
Polish enthusiasts already devoted themselves to space flights before World War II, although their work was not always understood.
I remember, for example, A. <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld's conference at the Warsaw astronomical observatory in which, on December 6, 1933, he presented his ideas on the pioneering study "Introduction to Cosmonautics".
The ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the attendees indifferent and, years later, <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld recalled that Dr. Jan Gadomski had been the only one who had shown interest in his work.
In 1934 <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld received in France the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Prize for his "Introduction to Cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966), mentioned above, later became a great driver of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and wrote a series of books devoted to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a promoter of cosmonautics, he was known worldwide and his contribution to science was rewarded when his name was given to one of the craters on the moon’s hidden face.
Already in 1925 a train was built in Poland that was to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, it is unknown who was the author of the proposal and the details of the project are not known either.
It is unclear whether the rocket would be used for the start of the dredge or for its braking.
The information about this dressin is limited to the collection in the press of the time.
From 1933 the Polish artillery began to devote itself to the missiles.
The research was funded by Komórka Techniki Uzrojenienia in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslawem Wolfkem and Prof. Gustawem Mokrzyckiegim.
From the preserved material, it becomes apparent that the research came to the stage of practical testing.
However, with the arrival of the German troops, the investigation was interrupted.
In 1937 appeared in the specialized press the prototype of a photoelectric fighter missile designed by the engineer Rohozi<0xC5><0x84>ski and the following year the study "Raketa - torpedo povietrzna i raketobomba lotnicza", by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocki, was published.
Both projects were intended for military use of missile engines.
Shortly before the war, the Provisional Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy) was responsible for all missile techniques projects for military use and coordinated all the work.
The committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity, it was interrupted by the start of the war.
Other studies dedicated to cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Society of Astronautics (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautice).
In the November 1954 issue of the magazine Problemy, for the first time, he refers to society with four very extensive articles dedicated to astronomy.
In one of them, Prof. M. Subotowicze proposed the creation of a society dedicated to cosmonautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was obvious that cosmic research was a discipline with future prospects.
Since the beginning of 1956 the Polish Society of Astronautics (PTA) aspired to be part of the International Federation of Astronautics (founded in 1951) and in the autumn of that year the PTA became a full member.
The following year the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902–1959), became the vice-president of the International Federation of Astronautics.
He held this position until his death in 1959.
Starting in 1956, the PTA significantly participated in the development of the RM rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which was a success and became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first type RM-1 was completed in 1957 and was first launched on October 10, 1958.
The rocket had a height of 1,800 meters, about 80 cm in length, and did not weigh up to 5 kg.
Later, the RM-1A version was completed and in the summer of 1959 the air tests of the two-stage RM-2 rockets began in the B<0xC5><0x82><0xC4><0x99>dów desert.
The rocket measured 1.4 meters and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another type of rocket in development would be the subject of a real scientific study. The RM-34 rocket would have a peak of 14.5 km and its mission would be to control the high wind.
However, in 1962 the work was suspended.
The successor of the first RM-type rockets was the Meteor-1 rocket, which was built during the years 1962 and 1965.
It was designed as a two-step rocket, with a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed, which differentiated from each other by the space available for the scientific apparatus.
In the Meteor-1A rocket the space available for the volume was 0.4 liters, in the Meteor-1B of 0.34 liters and in the Meteor-1C of 0.62 liters.
The maximum peak in the three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Air Institute, the first of which air tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a useful weight of 10 kg up to 60 km in height.
Subsequently, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
It is also necessary to mention the entry of Poland to the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the formation of the COSPAR national committee two years later.
As part of the Interkosmos program, Poland joined cosmic space research on Soviet artificial satellites and, in 1978, Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
Suspension of the Social Work Act is not the solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court suspended the law on social work.
The resolution aroused a heated discussion in society.
Of course, it will be interesting to examine the existing problem from a broader perspective.
Liberal economic systems in the EU, as in the globalised world, are based on the principle of greater economic and less regulatory competition.
Consequently, this means that the different economic forms and national economic systems are in permanent conflict with each other.
The cause lies in the principle of free trade and the free and unlimited movement of private capital, along with unbroken financial speculation.
The effect of the large differences in labour costs (salary) produces economic tensions.
Under this concept, it is necessary to understand the situation in which the manufacturer, with the import of cheap goods, attempts to shorten distances and for this "produces a decrease" of the competitor's price with the aim of making himself the most of the market and thus increasing his margin of profits.
On a large scale, for most employers, it means moving production abroad, buying cheaper there or disappearing. The result is a high unemployment in those countries where the price of labour, compared to other economies, is higher.
Because private capital has no social responsibility and is therefore not responsible for the unemployment generated by this phenomenon, the social expenditure of the state necessarily increases.
All of this contributes to the total disinterest of employers in paying taxes and compensating for the economic and social damage they have caused in their pursuit of profits.
The situation is so universally known that it is not necessary to present concrete statistical data.
Unscrupulous private capital practices create situations, in certain economies, in which the governments of those countries are forced to compete with the aim of artificially reducing the social level of the population itself and thereby attracting foreign capital to the country.
In other words, governments put private capital at the disposal of their own population without taking into account social decline.
This is especially evident in the changes to existing laws.
The goal is to force the population to accept the dictatorship of private capital, especially in terms of wages.
This occurs, on the one hand, through the system of economic obligation in the case of long-term unemployment; on the other hand, through the restricted right of employees in terms of labour rights.
The result is increasing poverty along with increasing disparities between the poor and the rich.
For a number of years, there have been food delivery points in Germany for poor people who can’t keep up with their own work.
The number of people receiving this type of aid is already in the million.
In the context of the increase in the competitiveness of the German economy, there is a fairly common case: people employed with such a low salary that the state must pay the rest to reach the minimum necessary to survive.
A scandal of this kind related to the situation of the auxiliary employees of the German federal parliament was made public.
The savings measures of virtually all the southern states of the EU lead undoubtedly to the same situation. People, pressured by an abysmal decline in their social level, are forced to emigrate as in the nineteenth century or to live poorly with a low salary on the border of society, with the hope that some day they will be able to capitalize.
Is it necessary to ask where it comes from?
In the case of other EU countries, then poverty moves from one country to another or never arrives, as Chinese, Indians, Brazilians, Turks, Moroccans, Egyptians or Africans continue to work for a small portion of a European wage.
This also affects all of Latin America.
Liberal theories and the media even claim to the satiety that the state should not provide capital to the economy, that directing the economy leads to its failure.
Private capital defends with nails and teeth the thesis that the state should not interfere in the economy by interfering in control.
It is then necessary to ask whether private capital does not influence with its selfishness the political march and, therefore, the whole state.
In this case, the answer is clearly affirmative.
The test is the existence of lobbies, in practice very powerful and omnipresent, in all states.
The result is a desperate situation that manifests itself in the field of corruption, in mutual favours, in legislation that is practically reprehensible everywhere but not punishable.
In Germany the situation is as follows: State ministries, in the absence of financial means, charge the drafting of law to private law firms, which are often linked to industry.
This type of bill is passed later in the Bundestag, the German parliament.
Thus, all power emanates not from the people, as announced in the constitutions of Western democracies, but from the strong financial groups representing their own interests.
It is obvious that democracies with a liberal orientation find themselves quickly in a situation such as the one described by Appian in his work The crisis of the Roman republic in the time of Caesar and Pompeii: "The state had long been disintegrating and the administrations occupied themselves by force."
In exchange for bribes, unlawfully obtained favors and help to finance stones or swords.
The rape and corruption spread without any hindrance and the people went to the urns with the crowded vote in advance"... "there were no people with character necessary to aspire to a post in the administration, so once, because of this disorganization, the state was a man in eight months without consuls, and it began to think of Caesar in the meantime."
The conclusion, like in antiquity, is that today’s society is based on unconsidered preferences of the individual benefit without taking into account the common interests.
Private capital is, in essence, unable to understand and claim the benefits of society as a whole.
The result is the same as then, an unprecedented decadence of the elite, without an effort to reform it in depth.
The causes of the rise of fascist and communist regimes must therefore be sought in the unbroken liberalization of economic systems in the 19th and 20th centuries.
With regard to the current situation, it is possible to consider the disappearance of these systems for the benefit of a liberal democracy, as a definite pause, pending the next coup.
The truly demolishing fact is that today’s elite completely ignores the losses of hundreds of thousands of lives, social and humanitarian disasters we have witnessed, as well as the crimes against humanity, as we know them in ancient and most recent history.
Suspension of the Public Procurement Act is not the solution; at least not in the long term.
Under pressure from economic competition, both internationally and within the EU, the government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to seek other ways to reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is, therefore, systemic.
The solution goes through concrete socio-political reforms, which both strengthen the participation of state capital and the influence of citizens in government and weaken the position of monopoly of private capital in society for the benefit of the state.
