Argo Movie: If it gets crude, call Hollywood
In November 1979, a group of Islamist students took over the U.S. embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats as hostages.
His release was to be in exchange for Shah Mohamed Réza Páhlevi, who after the revolution fled to the United States, a country that had sponsored his regime for decades.
For the U.S. administration, the situation did not offer any positive perspective: throwing the shah off the edge could not be allowed, since if it did, it would jeopardize the trust of its allies in other countries.
But the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution had led to the constitution of the theocratic regime, was not within their reach.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which later escalated further with the failed attempt to free the hostages by force.
The detained diplomats were released 444 days after the Algerian government's negotiating intervention.
In the United States, his destiny caused a wave of solidarity and animation against Iran.
Failure in Iran contributed decisively to Jimmy Carter's defeat against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film "Argo" by director and actor Ben Affleck focuses on an episode of this story, which harvested a small success for America.
Shortly before occupying the embassy, six employees of the building escaped.
After a complicated periplo, they ended up in the Canadian Embassy residence.
The CIA, in collaboration with the Canadian authorities, managed to pull them out of Iran, for which it helped a story covered up an extravagant point: they went out with Canadian passports, as members of the film crew examining the location in the country for filming a science fiction superproduction.
Combination of genres
The plan drawn by "exfiltration" expert Toni Mendez required Hollywood's collaboration.
To make the lie seem true, it was written about the film project in specialized magazines, press conferences were organized, the fictional production society even had a real office.
Details of the operation were kept secret for a long time, the film has been made from the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is a unique combination of several genres.
On the one hand, a realistic political thriller; on the other, a so-called "caper movie", the story of an episode that went well, a deception (an example may be the Ocean's Eleven series).
The film combines the moods. On the one hand we find well-documented sequences of Tehran. The credit sequence shows emblematic photographs of the time of events, which were plasmated in the same way in the film; there are not many differences in this regard.
On the other hand, Hollywood’s typical scenes are slightly lighter, marked by irony and a slight exaggeration.
And in addition, scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions: dressed men analyzing the situation at the negotiating table, in the halls of the office, by phone...
Ben Affleck has managed to restart his career in an excellent way.
The actor, who had been the subject of mockery, has become a respectable director and his way of acting has ceased to be the target of ironic comments.
Argo is his third feature film, after "Small Goodbye, Goodbye" (2007) and the thriller "The Town. City of Thieves" (2010).
At the same time, it's Affleck's first film in which the action doesn't take place in the city of Boston, where it grew up.
Also, the sensitivity of capturing the atmosphere of the place was a feature that placed old film directors above Hollywood standards.
And Affleck demonstrates it in Argo, where Tehran is "ruled" in Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in the streets, in the reconstruction of true events. The introductory sequence of taking the embassy is impressive for its synoptic ability which, at the same time, transmits the emotion of uncertainty and lack of prediction that arises when, somewhere, the story gives a passage.
Affleck and his collaborators get a similar effect on the fictional scenes (the imposing team in the Tehran bazaar).
Too much action in too many places
The director had to accept the fact that an explained story does not offer much in the cinematic sense of the most intriguing scenes.
Sometimes it adds something to the reality: here it doesn’t come out so elegantly (the scene in which the crisis at Tehran airport sharpens, the deviation from a call to America and the unbroken search behind its tracks turn into a madness).
Argo’s weakness is the disarray that arises from the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman have a very funny role as Hollywood collaborators, although their characters deserved more space and are not, much less, the only ones in this film.
For these reasons, Affleck’s film loses some dramatic trail, but it’s a film that can be followed with a moderate interest, assessing its performance and the retro style of a thriller that evokes the 1970s.
But if it collapses, it will be difficult.
As an evocation of a real story and as proof of how exaggerated the notions of omnipresence and omniscience of secret services can be, it is enough.
