The MVRDV architecture study shows that true adventures are not only in the head - in the example of the Spijkenisse library and the newly completed "book mountain" - 2 photos
“I think the building is fun, it has a futuristic look, and there’s finally something interesting to see,” says Lisette Verhaig, a crossing that passes through the street.
And Stefan Spermon, IT technician at a large company located near the library, points out: "In addition, the building is beautiful."
But I wonder why we need a library today.
We all have internet, tablets and e-books.
No one goes to those old-fashioned libraries for pleasure, right?
Spijkenisse, a dormitory city located at the gates of Róterdam that hardly deserves a fugitive visit, has the dubious honor of having risen with a record to forget.
The population of 80,000 people has the lowest literacy rate in the Netherlands.
To counter this embarrassing situation, a few years ago it was decided to contribute in some way to the general culture and copy the seven fictitious bridges that appear represented on the euro banknotes in the form of decorated armored concrete miniatures.
The success of the educational offensive was limited.
And that’s how the politicians decided that there was only one possibility to improve the statistics: we had to build a library!
Winy Maas, from the Dutch architecture studio MVRDV, a master in the art of bar diagrams and responsible for both fun and cynical buildings, took the subject with his usual serenity and appeared at the presentation of the contest in 2003 with five books under his arm and a smile on his face.
And as the jury looked perplexed around him and squeezed his shoulders, Maas proceeded to stack the books by size forming a pyramid and concluded his brief speech with the following words: "Dear fellow citizens:
Here you have it, my proposal for the Spijkenisse mountain of books, the so-called `Bookenberg'."
Nine years later, the <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>30 million mountain is raised at the expected location.
This is part of the revitalization project, which is completed with an underground parking lot, a supermarket, a post office and a couple of residential and townhouse buildings.
In early November, the mountain of books was awarded the second "Best Library of NL 2012" award.
In addition, the project is also nominated for the "Dutch National Wood Award 2012".
In this way, the small town lacking history, which to date had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian area and an incredibly ugly town hall behind whose white facade one would rather intuite a dairy plant, now has a work of contemporary architecture.
But above all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The Long Way to the Book
The first impression is that it is a paradise of books under a cheesecake.
It is true that there is an elevator that transports us right to the center of this mountainous massif, but true lovers of space and reading do not use it, but rather prefer to merge with its topography at every step of its climb to the top.
The fully glazed interior is bright and easy to cover with the view, the brick floor and the elegant lighthouses unambiguously support the public condition of the library.
The urban environment is perfect.
As you raise the view you can get to see the park benches, dogs and boys and girls playing football.
And everywhere books, books and more books.
"Normally book shelves are arranged along the facade and in the center a huge dark room opens which is usually somewhat uncomfortable and impersonal," says Winy Maas.
What we have done is to put legs up the classic spatial configuration and take the reading area from the inside to the outside.
The interior of the mountain is very well exploited: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the environmental education center and the maintenance room.
Special mention is deserved the black shelves that assume the functions of wall covering, parapet and shelf at the same time.
The sight, the touch and the smell are strange.
Even the most daily architects and civil engineers shake their heads when they hear about this unknown material.
“We wanted to work with recycled materials,” explains Joop Trouborst, project manager in the city of Spijkenisse.
And so it is like one day, on a Frisian farm, we encountered the right by-product from agriculture.
For many years, in the greenhouses and in the fields of the Netherlands, a plastic fabric of few millimeters of thickness is used as a basis for holding the roots of crops.
It is a cheap and efficient material.
This fine fabric lasts for two seasons and is then discarded.
For the library this fabric was pressed, for the first time in such quantities, until it obtained plates four centimeters thick.
With heat and pressure, so-called agricultural plastic (KLP) changes color and becomes a dark, homogeneous and resistant material that smells like a new car and sports shoes blend.
After 105 walks you reach the top of the mountain.
At the end of this continuous route of almost 500 meters around the mountain a reward awaits us: from the cafeteria you not only have a fantastic view of the city, but also you can enjoy tasty Dutch croquettes and its ficus planted in huge pots.
These create a pleasant pairing environment that keeps the atmospheric humidity suitable for this mountain of literature.
Donations for a new soul
“Although it’s hard to believe given its large glazed surfaces, this building is an exemplary project in terms of ecology,” says Trouborst.
The necessary heating and cooling are obtained from geothermal energy.
Despite the fact that the mountain of books is located under a huge glass pyramid, even on the sunny days the sun only shines for a few hours inside.
The huge wooden rings located in a transverse direction to the glass facade serve to give shadow and absorb most of the sun’s rays.
This creates a comfortable indoor climate.
The rest is about automatic blinds.
Stefan Spermon, a skeptical worker in the Information Technologies sector, has already dared to set foot in the new library.
And Lisette Verhaig has been there too.
Also, the Chinese traditional medicine teacher Cynthia Bogarde has visited the library. She qualifies the "Bookenberg" as Spijkenisse's "late soul".
The reason is that, on the occasion of the inauguration that took place a couple of weeks ago, all the inhabitants of the city were invited to donate a book from their private collection.
In this way, it is intended to fill, at the moment, the optical gaps of a library that does not yet have its full file; it currently has 70,000 copies.
The concept is quiet.
The shelves are full.
“There is nothing worse than a half-empty library,” says architect Winy Maas.
"I think thanks to our initiative now all residents have a certain connection with this building.
Everyone knows that his book is part of the library.
Even if it's just there to decorate.
In this way, the MVRDV study has achieved all success in that royal discipline that in the specialized argument is known as "creation of an identity".
The city of Spijkenisse has written a piece of the history of literature.
No matter how young and incult you may be.
Finally a starting point to shape your identity.
