But more and more academics and children’s development experts are praising the kindnesses of boredom.
According to them, it’s okay that, both us and our children, we get bored from time to time.
Boring forces the brain to look for interesting options and can encourage creativity.
Since most of us are currently connected to this or that screen, we do not experience the benefits that boredom brings.
So, should we accept boredom in good spirits?
Yeah. Yeah.
And no.
But we'll talk about it later.
First, like many people, I assumed that now that we have more time for leisure, boredom would be a relatively recent phenomenon.
But, as Peter Toohey, a professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary, Canada, and author of the book "Boredom: A Lively History" ("Boredom, an animated story") published in 2011 by Yale University Press, is not so.
“In fact, the history of boredom is very extensive,” he says.
In the walls of Pompeii there are graffiti in Latin about boredom dating from the 1st century AD.
We must also consider how we define boredom.
“The problem is that it has already been defined and discussed in many different ways,” says John D. Eastwood, professor of psychology at the University of York in Ontario, Canada.
After examining the published research and bringing the idea to a discussion group of 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues defined boredom as the experience of “desiring, but not being able, to participate in an activity that fills you.”
It states that the difference between boredom and apathy is that the person does not do something but wants to do it.
He pointed out that with apathy there is no desire to do something.
The main experience of boredom, he says, is “the alteration of the attention process, associated with a low mood and a feeling that time passes slowly.”
Boring can sound terribly similar to depression.
However, Professor Eastwood says that while they may be related, people who are bored tend to see the problem as an environmental or world issue, while people who are depressed consider the problem to be them.
Sometimes we think we are bored, when what actually happens to us is that we have trouble concentrating.
In his study "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention", published in the September issue of Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and colleagues referred to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a tape from a person reading a magazine article.
Some groups listened to a full-volume TV show in the adjoining room, others listened to it with low volume, so it was barely noticeable, while the third group did not listen to the audio at any time.
The group that listened to the program with the low volume showed more boredom than the other two groups; it cost them to concentrate, but they were not sure why and attributed it to boredom.
“When you try to focus on a difficult or interesting task, attention alteration can lead to boredom,” said Mark J. Fenske, professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph, Ontario, and one of the study’s authors.
“On the other hand, when you’re doing something boring, like detecting defective pieces on a manufacturing line, a music that distracts you can help you not get bored.”
“In fact, we currently know that moving or snoring, actions that are often interpreted as a sign of boredom, can actually help fight it, as they make that person physically more alert.”
“Research shows that those children who are allowed to move learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to remain silent,” says Professor Fenske.
We all know what it’s like to get bored at some point: the delay of an airplane, a monotonous speaker, a particularly boring film.
But some people tend to get bored more than others.
To help measure it, some researchers developed in the 1980s a “trend scale to boredom.”
The scale includes questions like “many of the things I have to do are repetitive and monotonous” and “there are so many things that interest me that I don’t have time to do everything.”
Stephen Vodanovich, professor of psychology at the University of West Florida, says that, using such scales, researchers have found that boys are more likely to get bored more often than girls, and specifically need more external and more varied stimulation.
But, in general, teens are a type of group that gets bored quite easily.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of human development and community at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted 400 teenagers and his parents between seven and eight times a day through a search.
