On the other hand, 3 percent of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson said he did not know whether the current boredom rates, 21 years later, would be higher or lower.
But he said what he did know was that “adolescence is a period in which boredom reaches its highest levels,” largely because both children and adolescents are not given great control over what they want to do.
So, back to my question from the beginning: is it good to get bored?
Sometimes it’s not, as it can lead to absurd physical risks, such as betting or falling into substance consumption as a method of combating it, as research shows.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers talk about the connection between boredom and creativity, according to Professor Vodanovich, who has been studying this issue for more than two decades.
“Boring is the way the brain tells you that you should be doing something else,” says Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at the University of New York.
But the brain does not always know what is most appropriate.
If you are bored and use that energy to play the guitar or cook, that will satisfy you.
But if you watch TV, it may satisfy you in the short term, but not in the long term.
“So, if your child is bored and you give him an iPad, he may no longer be bored, but he will not have learned to entertain himself or to dosage himself,” says Professor Fenske.
And "that ability to dosage itself applies to other situations," he notes.
Your child not only learns to entertain himself, but also learns to control himself better in other areas.
I don't think we really want to praise boredom.
But we shouldn’t be too critical of him either.
Our goal should be, rather, to feel comfortable away from the constant rumors of activities and technologies.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
“In our view, we need to get bored more, but boredom is a desire too anxious and disturbing to relate it to something worthwhile,” he says.
It points out that what people are really looking for is a way to disconnect and enjoy a dead time.
“In an environment where we are constantly overstimulated,” he says, “it’s hard to find ways to focus our attention when noise stops.”
