And remember that bad is good for those of apocalyptic mentality.
And he’s not the only teacher offering courses on “the end of the world” this semester, in theory the last in history.
At Temple, Deputy Professor Barry Vacker is teaching the course "Media, Culture and the End of the World".
Each week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
“We analyze why these ideas proliferate over time,” he said, and the way they offer hypothetical scenarios that guide certain human behavior.
If nuclear material falls into the hands of terrorists, for example, it could erupt a war.
This month, students analyzed movies with apocalyptic themes and explored how they compare with real-life examples.
“I’ve tried to inform students about what is possible, likely, credible, and impossible,” Vacker said.
On the main campus of the State University of Pennsylvania, Professor of Latin American History Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an assistant professor of Art History and Anthropology, have teamed up to deliver a course, titled only "The End of the World".
"We don't add '2012' to always count on the option to teach the course again, in case the world doesn't end," Restall said.
Despite the “imminent ruin,” students must study, generate projects, and take final exams.
At Penn State, the final exam will be taken on the eve of the Revelation, which leaves students no choice but to work “until the same night the world is supposed to end,” Restall said.
The courses were quite popular.
"It was saturated in two hours," Restall said of his course for high-average students, which was filled with 35 students.
We received emails for weeks and weeks before the start of the semester, from people asking if there was still a place.
Students, for their part, ensure that the course is one of the most interesting.
“It’s fascinating to see what people do to comfort themselves,” said Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old career student in Religion and Sociology from Haddonfield, New Jersey, at Rutgers-Camden.
And it is that the apocalyptic, secular or religious mentality, is only a matter of consolation or the absence of it.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old psychology and nursing career student, said he had seen all the apocalyptic films.
"I had never heard of a class that could teach that," he said.
I'm enjoying it.
But no student interviewed — and much less a teacher — said they believed in the December 21 deadline.
“Our first project focused on Mayan prophecy and in a way we discredit it,” said Julie Zeglen, a 21-year-old student at Temple, West Chester.
